          "body": "Paul never names the heresy systematically, but it surfaces in four overlapping faces: (a) **intellectual** — *philosophy and empty deception, the tradition of men* (2:8); (b) **ceremonial** — food, drink, festival, new moon, Sabbath (2:16); (c) **mystical** — *worship of the angels, taking his stand on visions* (2:18); (d) **ascetic** — *do not handle, do not taste, do not touch* (2:21). Scholars debate whether this was proto-Gnostic, Jewish mystical, Hellenistic mystery-religion, or some local Phrygian syncretism. The textual evidence points to all four blended — exactly what a Lycus Valley town would produce. What unifies them is the underlying claim that Christ alone is *not enough*."
